  <section*|INTRODUCTION>

  The classical sets of orthogonal polynomials of Jacobi, Laguerre, and
  Hermite satisfy second order differential equations, and also have the
  property that their derivatives form orthogonal systems. There is a fourth
  class of polynomials with these two properties, and similar in other ways
  to the other three classes, which has hitherto been little studied. We call
  these the <with|font-shape|italic|Bessel polynomials> because of their
  close relationship with the Bessel functions of half-integral order. They
  are orthogonal, but not in quite the same sense as the other three systems.
  The Bessel polynomials satisfy:

  <\equation>
    x<rsup|2>*<frac|d<rsup|2>*y|d*x<rsup|2>>+<around|(|2*x+2|)>*<frac|d*y|d*x>=n*<around|(|n+1|)>*y
  </equation>

  It will be shown that they occur naturally in the theory of traveling
  spherical waves.

  These polynomials seem to have been considered first by S. Bochner, who
  pointed out their connection with Bessel functions. They are also mentioned
  in a paper by W. Hahn. H. L. Krall treated them as orthogonal polynomials
  in a generalized sense. In the present paper they are studied in much
  greater detail. We derive their recurrence relations, weight function,
  generating function, normalizing factors, and the analogue of the Rodrigues
  formula. We discuss also their relation to Bessel functions and to the
  spherical waves.

  This paper is in two parts. The first part deals with Bessel polynomials
  proper. The second part deals with <with|font-shape|italic|generalized
  Bessel polynomials>, which satisfy the differential equation:

  <\equation>
    x<rsup|2>*y<rprime|''>+<around|(|a*x+b|)>*y<rprime|'>=n*<around|(|n+a-1|)>*y
  </equation>

  These specialize to the Bessel polynomials when <math|a=b=2>.

  The Bessel polynomials satisfy the differential equation:

  <\equation>
    x<rsup|2>*<frac|d<rsup|2>*y|d*x<rsup|2>>+<around|(|2*x+2|)>*<frac|d*y|d*x>=n*<around|(|n+1|)>*y
  </equation>

  where <math|n=0,1,2,\<ldots\>>. It is natural to extend this definition to
  negative subscripts by defining <math|y<rsub|-n><around|(|x|)>> to be
  <math|y<rsub|n-1><around|(|x|)>>. Thus <math|y<rsub|-1><around|(|x|)>=y<rsub|0><around|(|x|)>>,
  <math|y<rsub|-2><around|(|x|)>=y<rsub|1><around|(|x|)>>, and so on.

  Similarly, we define the <with|font-shape|italic|generalized Bessel
  polynomial> <math|y<rsub|n><around|(|x,a,b|)>> to be the polynomial of
  degree <math|n>, and with constant term equal to unity, which satisfies the
  differential equation:

  <\equation>
    x<rsup|2>*<frac|d<rsup|2>*y|d*x<rsup|2>>+<around|(|a*x+b|)>*<frac|d*y|d*x>=n*<around|(|n+a-1|)>*y
  </equation>

  where <math|n> is a non-negative integer, provided <math|a> is not a
  negative integer or zero, and <math|b> is not zero. The special case
  <math|a=b=2> gives the Bessel polynomials proper.

  <section*|Explicit formulas for the Bessel polynomials>

  From the differential equation (1) we derive at once the formula:

  <\equation>
    y<rsub|n><around|(|x|)>=<big|sum><rsub|k=0><rsup|n><frac|<around|(|n+k|)>!|<around|(|n-k|)>!k!><around*|(|<frac|x|2>|)><rsup|k>
  </equation>

  For convenience of reference we list the first six of these polynomials:

  <\equation>
    <tabular|<tformat|<table|<row|<cell|y<rsub|0><around|(|x|)>>|<cell|=1>>|<row|<cell|y<rsub|1><around|(|x|)>>|<cell|=1+x>>|<row|<cell|y<rsub|2><around|(|x|)>>|<cell|=1+3*x+3*x<rsup|2>>>|<row|<cell|y<rsub|3><around|(|x|)>>|<cell|=1+6*x+15*x<rsup|2>+15*x<rsup|3>>>|<row|<cell|y<rsub|4><around|(|x|)>>|<cell|=1+10*x+45*x<rsup|2>+105*x<rsup|3>+105*x<rsup|4>>>|<row|<cell|y<rsub|5><around|(|x|)>>|<cell|=1+15*x+105*x<rsup|2>+420*x<rsup|3>+945*x<rsup|4>+945*x<rsup|5>>>>>>
  </equation>

  These polynomials may be readily obtained from the recurrence relation:

  <\equation>
    y<rsub|n+1>=<around|(|2*n+1|)>*x*y<rsub|n>+y<rsub|n-1>
  </equation>

  which will be derived in Ÿ7. Note that the coefficients of the Bessel
  polynomials are positive integers.

  There is, of course, a second independent solution of the differential
  equation (1). This may be found by making the substitution
  <math|y=e<rsup|<frac|x|2>>*y<rsub|n>*<around|(|-x|)>>, which gives the
  solution: <math|y=e<rsup|x/2>*y<rsub|n>*<around|(|-x|)>>; accordingly the
  general solution of (1) is:

  <\equation>
    y=e<rsup|<frac|x|2>>*y<rsub|n>*<around|(|-x|)>
  </equation>

  <section*|The wave equation in spherical coordinates>

  The wave equation

  <\equation>
    \<Delta\>*u=<frac|1|c<rsup|2>>*<frac|\<partial\><rsup|2>*u|\<partial\>*t<rsup|2>>
  </equation>

  in spherical coordinates <math|R,\<theta\>,\<phi\>>, becomes

  <\equation>
    <frac|1|R>*<frac|\<partial\><rsup|2>|\<partial\>*R<rsup|2>>*<around|(|R*u|)>+<frac|1|sin
    \<theta\>>*<frac|\<partial\>|\<partial\>*\<theta\>><around*|(|sin
    \<theta\><frac|\<partial\>*u|\<partial\>*\<theta\>>|)>+<frac|1|sin<rsup|2>
    \<theta\>>*<frac|\<partial\><rsup|2>*u|\<partial\>*\<phi\><rsup|2>>=-<frac|1|c<rsup|2>>*<frac|\<partial\><rsup|2>*u|\<partial\>*t<rsup|2>>
  </equation>

  If this is solved by separation of variables, the radial factor
  <math|f<around|(|R|)>> is found to satisfy the differential equation:

  <\equation>
    R<rsup|2>*<frac|d<rsup|2>*f|d*R<rsup|2>>+2*R*<frac|d*f|d*R>+k<rsup|2>*R<rsup|2>*f=n*<around|(|n+1|)>*f
  </equation>

  where <math|k*c=\<omega\>>, and exp <math|<around|(|i*\<omega\>*t|)>> is
  the time factor. (See J. A. Stratton, <with|font-shape|italic|Electromagnetic
  theory>, pp. 440\U444.) If we let <math|r=k*R>, this becomes:

  <\equation>
    r<rsup|2>*<frac|d<rsup|2>*f|d*r<rsup|2>>+2*r*<frac|d*f|d*r>+r<rsup|2>*f=n*<around|(|n+1|)>*f
  </equation>

  It is well known that equation (6) may transformed into Bessel's equation
  by the substitution <math|f<around|(|r|)>=r<rsup|-1/2>*J<around|(|r|)>>,
  which yields:

  <\equation>
    r<rsup|2>*J<rprime|''>+r*J+r<rsup|2>*J=<around|(|n+1/2|)><rsup|2>*J
  </equation>

  If <math|n> is an integer, the solutions of (7) are Bessel functions of
  half-integral order. It is well known that these are elementary functions.

  However, it is simpler to treat equation (6) by making the substitution
  <math|f<around|(|r|)>=w<around|(|r|)>/r>, which gives the equation:

  <\equation>
    r<rsup|2>*<around|(|w<rprime|''>+w|)>=n*<around|(|n+1|)>*w
  </equation>

  Now real solutions of the wave equation found by separating the variables
  represent <with|font-series|bold|standing waves>. Two or more such
  solutions must be combined to get <with|font-series|bold|traveling waves>.
  There is, however, a standard method of obtaining traveling waves directly.
  This is to introduce the pure imaginary variable <math|z=i*k*R=i*r>. Then
  real and imaginary parts of a single solution of the wave equation
  represent traveling waves. Accordingly, in (8) we let <math|z=i*r> and
  <math|w<around|(|r|)>=e<rsup|-\<gamma\>*i*r><around|(|z|)>>. We then get:

  <\equation>
    z<rsup|2>*<around*|(|<frac|d<rsup|2>*y|d*z<rsup|2>>-2*<frac|d*y|d*z>|)>=n*<around|(|n+1|)>*y
  </equation>

  For integral values of <math|n>, (9) has solutions which are polynomials in
  <math|1/z>. Therefore we make the final substitution
  <math|x=1/z=1/<around|(|i*k*R|)>>, and obtain (1). This is the equation for
  Bessel polynomials. It follows that the wave equation in spherical
  coordinates has solutions of the form:

  <\equation>
    u<around|(|R,\<theta\>,\<phi\>|)>=R<rsup|-1>*P<rsub|n><rsup|m><around|(|cos
    \<theta\>|)>*sin <around|(|m*\<phi\>-\<omega\>*t|)>*e<rsup|-i*\<omega\>*t>*y<rsub|n>*<around|(|1/i*k*R|)>
  </equation>

  where <math|y<rsub|n><around|(|x|)>=y<rsub|n>*<around|(|1/i*k*R|)>> is a
  Bessel polynomial, and <math|k*c=\<omega\>>. Note that the real and
  imaginary parts of (10) represent waves traveling in the radial direction
  with velocity <math|c>. Formula (10) makes evident the elementary nature of
  this type of solution and suggests a treatment of spherical waves based on
  a theory of the functions <math|y<rsub|n><around|(|x|)>> considered as a
  class of orthogonal polynomials, rather than on the usual theory of Bessel
  functions.

  <section*|The relation of Bessel polynomials to Bessel functions>

  In the preceding <math|Ÿ*3>, equation (7) is the differential equation for
  Bessel functions of order <math|n+1/2>. Keeping track of the
  transformations connecting equations (1), (7), (8), and (9), and comparing
  coefficients, we find the following formulas connecting the Bessel
  polynomials and Bessel functions:

  <\align>
    <tformat|<table|<row|<cell|J<rsub|n+<frac|1|2>><around|(|r|)>>|<cell|=<sqrt|\<pi\>*r>**<frac|2<rsup|i*r>|2><around*|[|e<rsup|i*\<pi\>*<around*|(|n+<frac|1|2>|)>>*y<rsub|n>*<around*|(|<frac|1|r>|)>+e<rsup|-i*\<pi\>*<around*|(|n+<frac|1|2>|)>>*y<rsub|n>*<around*|(|<frac|1|r>|)>|]><eq-number>>>|<row|<cell|J<rsub|n+1/2><around|(|r|)>>|<cell|=<around|(|2*\<pi\>*r|)><rsup|-1/2>*<around*|[|e<rsup|-i*\<pi\>>*e<rsup|i*\<gamma\><rsub|n>>*y<rsub|n>*<around|(|-1/i*r|)>+i<rsup|n>*e<rsup|-i*\<gamma\><rsub|n>>*y<rsub|n>*<around|(|1/i*r|)>|]><eq-number>>>|<row|<cell|J<rsub|n-1/2><around|(|r|)>>|<cell|=<around|(|2*\<pi\>*r|)><rsup|-1/2>*<around*|[|i*e<rsup|\<gamma\><rsub|n>>*y<rsub|n>*<around|(|-1/i*r|)>+i<rsup|-n>*e<rsup|-\<gamma\><rsub|n>>*y<rsub|n>*<around|(|1/i*r|)>|]><eq-number>>>>>
  </align>

  Schelkunoff (<with|font-shape|italic|Electromagnetic waves>, pp. 51\U52)
  and P. M. Morse (<with|font-shape|italic|Vibration and sound>, pp.
  246\U247) define the spherical Bessel functions
  <math|J<rsub|n><around|(|r|)>>, <math|N<rsub|n><around|(|r|)>>, and
  <math|j<rsub|n><around|(|r|)>>, <math|m<rsub|n><around|(|r|)>>, which are
  solutions of our differential equations (8) and (6) respectively. These
  functions are related to the Bessel functions of half-integral order, and
  hence to the Bessel polynomials. The latter relations are:

  <\align>
    <tformat|<table|<row|<cell|y<rsub|n>*<around|(|-1/i*r|)>>|<cell|=e<rsup|-i*\<gamma\><rsub|n>>*J<rsub|n><around|(|r|)>-i<rsup|-n>*N<rsub|n><around|(|r|)><eq-number>>>|<row|<cell|J<rsub|n><around|(|r|)>>|<cell|=<around*|[|i<rsup|-n>*e<rsup|i*\<gamma\><rsub|n>>*y<rsub|n>*<around|(|-1/i*r|)>+i<rsup|n+1>*e<rsup|-i*\<gamma\><rsub|n>>*y<rsub|n>*<around|(|1/i*r|)>|]>/2<eq-number>>>|<row|<cell|N<rsub|n><around|(|r|)>>|<cell|=-<around*|[|i<rsup|-n>*e<rsup|i*\<gamma\><rsub|n>>*y<rsub|n>*<around|(|-1/i*r|)>+i<rsup|-n>*e<rsup|-i*\<gamma\><rsub|n>>*y<rsub|n>*<around|(|1/i*r|)>|]>/2<eq-number>>>>>
  </align>

  in the case of the Schelkunoff functions <math|J<rsub|n><around|(|r|)>> and
  <math|N<rsub|n><around|(|r|)>>. Likewise we have:

  <\align>
    <tformat|<table|<row|<cell|j<rsub|n><around|(|r|)>>|<cell|=<around|(|1/2*r|)>*<around*|[|i<rsup|-n>*e<rsup|i*\<gamma\><rsub|n>>*y<rsub|n>*<around|(|-1/i*r|)>+i<rsup|n+1>*e<rsup|-i*\<gamma\><rsub|n>>*y<rsub|n>*<around|(|1/i*r|)>|]><eq-number>>>|<row|<cell|m<rsub|n><around|(|r|)>>|<cell|=<around|(|1/2*r|)>*<around*|[|i<rsup|n>*e<rsup|i*\<gamma\><rsub|n>>*y<rsub|n>*<around|(|-1/i*r|)>+i<rsup|-n+1>*e<rsup|-i*\<gamma\><rsub|n>>*y<rsub|n>*<around|(|1/i*r|)>|]><eq-number>>>>>
  </align>

  Bessel polynomials form an orthogonal system, the weight function being
  <math|e<rsup|-2*\<pi\>*x>> and the path of integration the unit circle in
  the complex plane. The weight function and the path are not unique; an
  arbitrary analytic function may be added to the weight function, the weight
  function may be multiplied by a nonzero constant, and the unit circle may
  be replaced by an arbitrary curve around the origin. Formula (10) shows
  that in applications to spherical waves we are interested in pure imaginary
  values of the argument <math|x>. This suggests a path of integration along
  the imaginary axis; but we find the unit circle a more convenient path for
  deriving formulas.

  To prove orthogonality we first note that the differential equation (1) may
  be written in the form:

  <\equation>
    <around|(|x<rsup|2>*e<rsup|-2*\<pi\>*x>*y<rsub|n><rprime|'>|)><rprime|'>=n*<around|(|n+1|)>*e<rsup|-2*\<pi\>*x>*y<rsub|n>
  </equation>

  Integrating by parts counter-clockwise around the unit circle we find:

  <\equation>
    <around|(|n+1|)>*<big|int><rsub|u>y<rsub|m>*y<rsub|n>*e<rsup|-2*\<pi\>*x>*d*x=<big|int><rsub|u><around|(|x<rsup|2>*e<rsup|-2*\<pi\>*x>*y<rsub|n><rprime|'>|)><rprime|'>*y<rsub|m>*d*x=-<big|int><rsub|u>x<rsup|2>*e<rsup|-2*\<pi\>*x>*y<rsub|n><rprime|'>*y<rsub|m><rprime|'>*d*x
  </equation>

  Interchanging <math|m> and <math|n> and subtracting, we get:

  <\equation>
    <big|int><rsub|u>y<rsub|m>*y<rsub|n>*e<rsup|-2*\<pi\>*x>*d*x=0\<forall\>m\<neq\>n.
  </equation>

  This is the required orthogonality relation.

  <section*|Rodrigues' formula>

  Corresponding to Rodrigues' formula for the Legendre polynomials, and to
  similar well known formulas for the Hermite, Laguerre, and Jacobi
  polynomials, we now express the Bessel polynomials
  <math|y<rsub|n><around|(|x|)>> in terms of the <math|n>th derivative of a
  multiple of the weight function <math|e<rsup|-2*\<pi\>*x>>:

  <\equation>
    y<rsub|n><around|(|x|)>=2<rsup|n>*e<rsup|2*\<pi\>*x>*<frac|d<rsup|n>|d*x<rsup|n>>*<around|(|x<rsup|n>*e<rsup|-2*\<pi\>*x>|)>
  </equation>

  Here the factor <math|2<rsup|n>> is to make the constant term equal to
  unity. Note that the right side of (18) is a polynomial of degree <math|n>.
  For <math|k\<less\>n>, this polynomial is orthogonal to <math|x<rsup|k>>,
  with weight function and path as before, that is:

  <\equation>
    <frac|1|2*\<pi\>*i>*<big|int><rsub|u>x<rsup|k-n>*<frac|d<rsup|n>|d*x<rsup|n>>*<around|(|x<rsup|n>*e<rsup|-2*\<pi\>*x>|)>*d*x=0
  </equation>

  for <math|k=0,1,2,\<ldots\>,n-1>. This may be seen by integrating by parts
  <math|k+1> times around the unit circle. But by formula (17), the Bessel
  polynomial <math|y<rsub|n><around|(|x|)>> is also orthogonal to
  <math|x<rsup|k>> with the same path and weight function. Since this
  property determines uniquely up to a multiplicative constant a polynomial
  of degree <math|n>, and since the constant terms are both unity, it follows
  that the two sides of (18) are identical. Formula (18) may also be verified
  directly, using the explicit formula (3). In the same manner it may be
  shown more generally that with <math|k> an integer,
  <math|k<rsup|n>=k*<around|(|k-1|)>*\<cdots\>*<around|(|k-n+1|)>>:

  <\equation>
    <frac|1|2*\<pi\>*i>*<big|int><rsub|u>x<rsup|n>*y<rsub|n><around|(|x|)>*e<rsup|-2*\<pi\>*x>*d*x=<frac|<around|(|-2|)><rsup|k>*k!<around|(|n|)>|<around|(|n+k+1|)>!>
  </equation>

  <section*|Recurrence relations for the Bessel polynomials>

  Among the infinitely many recurrence relations for the Bessel polynomials,
  we list the following five as being the most useful or interesting. They
  resemble in some ways the relations for the Bessel functions, and in other
  ways the relations for the classical orthogonal polynomials.

  <\equation>
    <tabular|<tformat|<table|<row|<cell|y<rsub|n><around*|(|x|)>>|<cell|=<around|(|2*n-1|)>*x*y<rsub|n-1><around*|(|x|)>+y<rsub|n-2><around*|(|x|)>>>|<row|<cell|x<rsup|2>*y<rprime|'><rsub|n>>|<cell|=<around|(|n*x-1|)>*y<rsub|n>+y<rsub|n-1>>>|<row|<cell|x<rsup|2>*y<rprime|'><rsub|n-1>>|<cell|=y<rsub|n>-<around|(|n*x+1|)>*y<rsub|n-1>>>|<row|<cell|x*<around|(|y<rprime|'><rsub|n>+y<rprime|'><rsub|n-1>|)>>|<cell|=n*<around|(|y<rsub|n>-y<rsub|n-1>|)>>>|<row|<cell|<around|(|n*x+1|)>*y<rprime|'><rsub|n>+y<rprime|'><rsub|n-1>>|<cell|=n<rsup|2>*y<rsub|n>>>>>>
  </equation>

  The recurrence relations (21) may be derived from the well known recurrence
  relations for the Bessel functions, using the relations (11). They may also
  be derived from the explicit formula (3), or by making use of the
  orthogonality of the Bessel polynomials. The latter method is described
  below in <math|Ÿ*16>, where the recurrence relations (51) for the
  generalized Bessel polynomials are obtained. These correspond to the first
  two relations of (21), which are included as the special case where
  <math|a=b=2>. Consequently the details of the derivation of relations (21)
  will be omitted.

  <section*|The normalizing factor>

  If a function <math|f<around|(|x|)>> is formally expanded in an infinite
  series of Bessel polynomials:

  <\equation*>
    f<around|(|x|)>\<sim\><big|sum><rsub|n=0><rsup|\<infty\>>f<rsub|n>*y<rsub|n><around|(|x|)>
  </equation*>

  the coefficients <math|f<rsub|n>> are given by

  <\equation>
    f<rsub|n>=<frac|<big|int>f<around|(|x|)>*y<rsub|n><around|(|x|)>*e<rsup|-2*\<pi\>*x>*d*x|<big|int>y<rsub|n><around|(|x|)><rsup|2>*e<rsup|-2*\<pi\>*x>*d*x>
  </equation>

  Hence it is desirable to know the value of the integral in the denominator.
  We evaluate this integral by using formula (20) with <math|n=k>. This
  gives:

  <\equation>
    <frac|1|2*\<pi\>*i>*<big|int>y<rsub|n><around|(|x|)><rsup|2>*e<rsup|-2*\<pi\>*x>*d*x=<frac|1|2*\<pi\>*i>*<frac|2*n!|n!><big|int><around*|(|<frac|x|2>|)><rsup|n>*y<rsub|n><around|(|x|)>*e<rsup|-2*\<pi\>*x>*d*x=<frac|2<around|(|-1|)><rsup|n+1>|2*n+1>
  </equation>

  It is curious to note that except for the alternating sign, this is the
  same as the normalizing factor for the Legendre polynomials. It follows
  from (23) that the polynomials:

  <\equation>
    <around*|(|1+<frac|i|2>|)><rsup|n><sqrt|<frac|2*n+1|2*\<pi\>>><rsup|>*y<rsub|n><around|(|x|)>
  </equation>

  form an orthonormal set with weight function <math|e<rsup|-2*\<pi\>*x>> and
  path of integration the unit circle.

  <section*|The generating function for Bessel polynomials>

  In view of formula (3), a generating function <math|G<around|(|x,t|)>> of
  the usual kind would have the form:

  <\equation>
    G<around|(|x,t|)>=<big|sum><rsub|n=0><rsup|\<infty\>>y<rsub|n><around|(|x|)>*t<rsup|n>=<big|sum><rsub|n=0><rsup|\<infty\>><frac|<around|(|2*n|)>!|n!<rsup|2><around|(|1-t|)><rsup|2*n+1>>*<around|(|x*t|)><rsup|n>
  </equation>

  However, since this series converges only for <math|t/<around|(|1-t|)>=0>,
  we replace <math|t<rsup|n>> by <math|t<rsup|n>/n>!, which gives:

  <\equation>
    exp <around*|(|1-<around|(|1-2*x*t|)><rsup|1/2>|)>=<big|sum><rsub|n=0><rsup|\<infty\>>y<rsub|n-1><around|(|x|)><frac|t<rsup|n>|n!>
