  <section*|The moments of the weight function>

  If we consider the weight function to be
  <math|e<rsup|-2*\<pi\>*x>/2*\<pi\>*i> rather than
  <math|e<rsup|-2*\<pi\>*x>>, then its moments, with the unit circle as path
  of integration, are given by:

  <\equation>
    a<rsub|n>=<frac|1|2*\<pi\>*i>*<big|int>x<rsup|n>*e<rsup|-2*\<pi\>*x>*d*x=<around|(|-2|)><rsup|n+1>*<around|(|n+1|)>!
  </equation>

  <section*|In the theory of orthogonal polynomials>

  It is often important to know the value of determinant:

  <\equation>
    \<Delta\><rsub|n>=<det|<tformat|<table|<row|<cell|a<rsub|0>>|<cell|a<rsub|1>>|<cell|\<cdots\>>|<cell|a<rsub|n-1>>>|<row|<cell|a<rsub|1>>|<cell|a<rsub|2>>|<cell|\<cdots\>>|<cell|a<rsub|n>>>|<row|<cell|\<vdots\>>|<cell|\<vdots\>>|<cell|\<ddots\>>|<cell|\<vdots\>>>|<row|<cell|a<rsub|n-1>>|<cell|a<rsub|n>>|<cell|\<cdots\>>|<cell|a<rsub|2*n-2>>>>>>
  </equation>

  This determinant is discussed in H. L. Krall [3, 4]. In particular we wish
  to verify that it is never zero, in order to conclude that polynomials
  which are orthogonal with the given weight function and path of integration
  are uniquely determined, up to a multiplicative constant, by this property.
  This was assumed in deriving the Rodrigues' formula in <math|Ÿ*6>.
  Accordingly, we substitute the value of <math|a<rsub|n>> from (30) into
  (31) and evaluate the resulting determinant by repeated subtraction of
  rows. We omit the details of this evaluation and give only the result:

  <\equation>
    \<Delta\><rsub|n>=<around|(|-1|)><rsup|<around|(|n-1|)>/2>*<around|(|-2|)><rsup|n<rsup|2>><frac|<around|(|n-1|)>!|<big|prod><rsub|s=-1><rsup|2*n-1>s!>
  </equation>

  We conclude from formula (32) that <math|\<Delta\><rsub|n>> is never zero.

  <section*|Part II. Generalized Bessel Polynomials>

  <subsection*|The differential equation>

  As defined in <math|Ÿ*1>, the generalized Bessel polynomial
  <math|y<rsub|n><around|(|x,a,b|)>> is the polynomial of degree <math|n> and
  with constant term equal to unity, which satisfies the differential
  equation:

  <\equation>
    x<rsup|2>*y<rprime|''>+<around|(|a*x+b|)>*y<rprime|'>=n*<around|(|n+a-1|)>*y
  </equation>

  where the Bessel polynomials proper is the special case of (2) where
  <math|a=b=2>. We assume that <math|b> is not zero. With <math|b=0>, the
  general solution of (2) is <math|y=A*x<rsup|n>+B*x<rsup|-n>>. We exclude
  also the cases where <math|a> is zero or a negative integer, as these are
  better developed below breaks down in those cases, and a special treatment
  is required. The value of the constant <math|b> is not important, since it
  is covered. Note that the derivative <math|y<rprime|'>> of a solution of
  (2) satisfies the equation:

  <\equation>
    x<rsup|2>*<frac|d<rsup|2>*y<rprime|'>|d*x<rsup|2>>+<around|(|a*x+2*x+b|)>*<frac|d*y<rprime|'>|d*x>=n*<around|(|n+a+1|)>*y<rprime|'>
  </equation>

  which has the form of (2), but with <math|a> replaced by <math|a+2>. It
  follows that the derivatives of generalized Bessel polynomials are
  generalized Bessel polynomials, and also that the polynomials in the
  excluded cases where <math|a=0,-1,-2,\<ldots\>> can be obtained by repeated
  integration from the polynomials with <math|a=1> or <math|2>.

  We proceed now to develop a theory of the generalized Bessel polynomials
  roughly parallel to that given for the Bessel polynomials proper. When
  <math|a> is an integer, the two theories are very similar. There are
  certain differences, however, when <math|a> is nonintegral.

  <section*|Explicit formulas for the generalized Bessel polynomials>

  Instead of the notation <math|y<rsub|n><around|(|x,a,b|)>> for these
  polynomials, we shall often use the shorter forms
  <math|y<rsub|n><around|(|x|)>> or <math|y<rsub|n>>. Solving in the usual
  manner we find the explicit formula:

  <\equation>
    y<rsub|n><around|(|x,a,b|)>=<big|sum><rsub|k=0><rsup|n>C<rsub|n,k>*<around|(|n+k+a-2|)><around|(|k|)><around*|(|<frac|x|b>|)><rsup|k>
  </equation>

  where <math|C<rsub|n,k>> is a binomial coefficient, and
  <math|<around|(|x|)><around|(|k|)>> as usual means
  <math|x*<around|(|x-1|)>*\<cdots\>*<around|(|x-k+1|)>>. The first five of
  these polynomials are therefore given by:

  <\align*>
    <tformat|<table|<row|<cell|y<rsub|0><around|(|x|)>>|<cell|=1>>|<row|<cell|y<rsub|1><around|(|x|)>>|<cell|=1+a<around*|(|<frac|x|b>|)>>>|<row|<cell|y<rsub|2><around|(|x|)>>|<cell|=1+2*<around|(|a+1|)><around*|(|<frac|x|b>|)>+<around|(|a+1|)>*<around|(|a+2|)><around*|(|<frac|x|b>|)><rsup|2>>>|<row|<cell|y<rsub|3><around|(|x|)>>|<cell|=1+3*<around|(|a+2|)><around*|(|<frac|x|b>|)>+3*<around|(|a+2|)>*<around|(|a+3|)><around*|(|<frac|x|b>|)><rsup|2>+<around|(|a+2|)>*<around|(|a+3|)>*<around|(|a+4|)><around*|(|<frac|x|b>|)><rsup|3>>>|<row|<cell|y<rsub|4><around|(|x|)>>|<cell|=1+4*<around|(|a+3|)><around*|(|<frac|x|b>|)>+6*<around|(|a+3|)>*<around|(|a+4|)><around*|(|<frac|x|b>|)><rsup|2>+4*<around|(|a+3|)>*<around|(|a+4|)>*<around|(|a+5|)><around*|(|<frac|x|b>|)><rsup|3>>>|<row|<cell|>|<cell|<space|1em>+<around|(|a+3|)>*<around|(|a+4|)>*<around|(|a+5|)>*<around|(|a+6|)><around*|(|<frac|x|b>|)><rsup|4>>>>>
  </align*>

  The coefficients are no longer necessarily integral, as was the case with
  the Bessel polynomials proper. Note that in the excluded cases
  <math|a=0,-1,-2,\<ldots\>> one or more of the polynomials
  <math|y<rsub|n><around|(|x|)>> are of degree less than <math|n>. If
  <math|a> is not an integer, the second solution of (2) is not an elementary
  function, but it may be represented by an infinite series, or in terms of
  integrals of elementary functions.

  <section*|The weight function and its moments>

  We shall show that the generalized Bessel polynomials form an orthogonal
  system, with path of integration an arbitrary curve surrounding the zero
  point, and with weight function <math|p<around|(|x|)>> given by:

  <\equation>
    p<around|(|x|)>=<frac|1|2*\<pi\>*i>*<big|sum><rsub|n=0><rsup|\<infty\>><frac|\<Gamma\><around|(|a|)>|\<Gamma\>*<around|(|a+n-1|)>>*<around*|(|-<frac|b|x>|)><rsup|n>
  </equation>

  The series in (36) clearly converges for all <math|x> except zero.
  Expanding (36) gives:

  <\equation>
    p<around|(|x|)>=<frac|1|2*\<pi\>*i>*<around*|[|a-1+<frac|<around|(|-b/x|)>|a>+<frac|<around|(|-b/x|)><rsup|2>|a*<around|(|a+1|)>>+<frac|<around|(|-b/x|)><rsup|3>|a*<around|(|a+1|)>*<around|(|a+2|)>>+<frac|<around|(|-b/x|)><rsup|4>|a*<around|(|a+1|)>*<around|(|a+2|)>*<around|(|a+3|)>>+\<ldots\>|]>
  </equation>

  Formula (37) would clearly have to be modified for the excluded cases
  <math|a=0,-1,-2,\<ldots\>>. Note that <math|p<around|(|x|)>> reduces to the
  previous weight function <math|e<rsup|-2*\<pi\>*x>/2*\<pi\>*i> for the case
  <math|a=b=2> of Bessel polynomials proper. The function
  <math|p<around|(|x|)>> differs, except when <math|a=1> or <math|2>, from
  the function <math|\<sigma\><around|(|x|)>> given by

  <\equation>
    \<sigma\><around|(|x|)>=x<rsup|a>*e<rsup|-b*<space|0.17em>x>/2*\<pi\>*i
  </equation>

  which is the factor needed to make equation (2) self-adjoint, and which is
  therefore a natural candidate for a weight function. However,
  <math|\<sigma\><around|(|x|)>> is multiple-valued when <math|a> is not an
  integer, and this is inconvenient if we wish to integrate around the point
  <math|x=0>. The function <math|\<sigma\><around|(|x|)>> satisfies the
  differential equation:

  <\equation>
    <around|(|x<rsup|2>*\<sigma\><rprime|'>|)>=<around|(|a*x+b|)>*\<sigma\>,
  </equation>

  while <math|p<around|(|x|)>> satisfies the related nonhomogeneous equation:

  <\equation>
    <around|(|x<rsup|2>*p<rprime|'>|)>=<around|(|a*x+b|)>*p-<frac|<around|(|a-1|)>*<around|(|a-2|)>|2*\<pi\>*i>*x
  </equation>

  These equations are the same if <math|a> is <math|1> or <math|2>, which
  suggests that the special case where <math|a> is <math|1> may be of equal
  importance with the case where <math|a> is <math|2> which we have treated
  in Part I.

  Formula (36) for <math|p<around|(|x|)>> may be obtained by finding the
  solution of equation (40) of the form <math|p<around|(|x|)>=<big|sum><rsub|n=0><rsup|\<infty\>>c<rsub|n>*x<rsup|n>>.
  However, formula (36) for <math|p<around|(|x|)>> was actually arrived at as
  follows: The moments

  <\equation>
    a<rsub|n>=<frac|1|2*\<pi\>*i>*<big|int>x<rsup|n>*p<around|(|x|)>*e<rsup|-2*\<pi\>*x>*d*x
  </equation>

  \ for a set of orthogonal polynomials satisfying (2) obey the recurrence
  relation:

  <\equation>
    <around|(|n+a-1|)>*a<rsub|n>+b*a<rsub|n-1>=0
  </equation>

  (see H. L. Krall [3, 4]). Hence, taking <math|a<rsub|0>=-b>, the moments
  must be given by:

  <\equation>
    a<rsub|n-1>=<frac|\<Gamma\><around|(|a|)>|\<Gamma\>*<around|(|a+n-1|)>>*<around|(|-b|)><rsup|n>
  </equation>

  From (42) the coefficients in (36) may be obtained immediately by
  multiplying by <math|x<rsup|n>> and integrating around the unit circle.
  Conversely, it may be verified that the function <math|p<around|(|x|)>> as
  given by (36) has the moments given by (42).

  Since we now have a formula for the moments, we may calculate the
  determinant <math|\<Delta\><rsub|n>>, as defined by formula (31) for the
  generalized Bessel polynomials. Substituting the value of <math|a<rsub|n>>
  from (42) into (31) and evaluating as before by repeated subtraction of
  rows, we find:

  <\equation>
    \<Delta\><rsub|n>=<around|(|-1|)><rsup|<around|(|n-1|)>/2>*<around|(|-b|)><rsup|n<rsup|2>><frac|<around|(|n-1|)>!|<big|prod><rsub|s=-1><rsup|2*n-3><around|(|a+s|)>>
  </equation>

  It can be seen from (43) that <math|\<Delta\><rsub|n>> is never zero except
  in the excluded cases <math|a=0,-1,-2,\<ldots\>>.

  <section*|Orthogonality of the generalized Bessel polynomials>

  If equation (2) is multiplied by <math|p<around|(|x|)>>, it may be written
  in the form:

  <\equation>
    <around|(|x<rsup|2>*p<around|(|x|)>*y<rsub|n><rprime|'>|)><rprime|'>+a*<around|(|x-1|)>*<around|(|a-2|)>*y<rsub|n><rprime|'>*2*\<pi\>*i=n*<around|(|n+a-1|)>*p*y<rsub|n>
  </equation>

  This follows from the fact that <math|p<around|(|x|)>> satisfies equation
  (40). If we now multiply equation (44) by <math|y<rsub|k>> and integrate
  around the unit circle we get:

  <\equation>
    n*<around|(|n+a-1|)>*<big|int>y<rsub|n>*y<rsub|k>*p*d*x=<big|int><around|(|x<rsup|2>*p<around|(|x|)>*y<rsub|n><rprime|'>|)><rprime|'>*y<rsub|k>*d*x+<around|(|a-1|)>*<around|(|a-2|)>*<frac|1|2*\<pi\>*i>*<big|int>x<rsup|2>*y<rsub|n><rprime|'>*y<rsub|k>*d*x
  </equation>

  Interchanging <math|n> and <math|k> in (45) and subtracting gives:

  <\equation>
    <big|int>y<rsub|n>*y<rsub|k>*p*d*x=0\<forall\>n\<neq\>k
  </equation>

  which shows that the polynomials are orthogonal with <math|p<around|(|x|)>>
  as weight function.

