    \;
  </equation*>

  <\equation*>
    .
  </equation*>

  But since we have:

  <\equation>
    <big|sum><rsub|s=0><rsup|\<infty\>><around|(|-1|)><rsup|s>*C<rsub|k,s>*<around|(|A-s|)><rsup|<around|(|n|)>>=<choice|<tformat|<table|<row|<cell|0,>|<cell|<text|for
    >k\<gtr\>n>>|<row|<cell|n<around|(|k|)>*<around|(|A-k|)><rsup|<around|(|n-k|)>>,>|<cell|<text|for
    >k\<leq\>n>>>>><text|>
  </equation>

  the final expression in (48) reduces to:

  <\equation>
    <big|sum><rsub|k=0><rsup|n>x<rsup|-k>*b<rsup|k-n>*k*<around|(|2*n+a-2-k|)><rsup|<around|(|n-k|)>>=<big|sum><rsub|k=0><rsup|n>C<rsub|n,k>*<around|(|n+a-2-k|)><around|(|b|)><around*|(|<frac|x|b>|)><rsup|k>*y<rsub|n><around|(|x,a,b|)>
  </equation>

  Consequently, we have (47).

  <section*|Recurrence relations for the generalized Bessel polynomials>

  The recurrence relations given by formulas (21) have analogues for the
  generalized Bessel polynomials. However, some of these are much more
  complicated than those for the Bessel polynomials proper, although they
  simplify considerably for certain integral values of <math|a>. Because they
  are so complicated we shall give only the following two:

  <\equation>
    <tabular|<tformat|<table|<row|<cell|<around|(|n+a-1|)>*<around|(|2*n+a-2|)>*y<rsub|n+1>>>|<row|<cell|=<around|[|<around|(|2*n+a|)>*<around|(|2*n+a-2|)><around|(|<frac|x|b>|)>+a-2|]>*<around|(|2*n+a-1|)>*y<rsub|n>+n*<around|(|2*n+a|)>*y<rsub|n-1>>>>>>
  </equation>

  <\equation>
    x<rsup|2>*<around|(|2*n+a-2|)>*y<rprime|'><rsub|n>=<around|[|n*<around|(|2*n+a-2|)>*x-b*n|]>*y<rsub|n>+b*n*y<rsub|n-1>
  </equation>

  These correspond to the first two relations of (21), as may be seen by
  placing <math|a=b=2>. The first relation of (51) has the standard form:

  <\equation>
    y<rsub|n+1>=<around|(|A*x+B|)>*y<rsub|n>+C*y<rsub|n-1>
  </equation>

  which is the usual type of recurrence relation for orthogonal polynomials.
  Since the method of determining the coefficients <math|A>, <math|B>, and
  <math|C> by using orthogonality is familiar, we shall prove only the second
  relation of (51). The first relation may be proved in a similar manner.

  To prove the second relation of (51), we first select the constant <math|A>
  so that <math|x<rsup|2>*y<rsub|n><rprime|'>-A*x*y<rsub|n>> is a polynomial
  of degree <math|n>. It then has an expansion of the form:

  <\equation>
    x<rsup|2>*y<rsub|n><rprime|'>-A*x*y<rsub|n>=<big|sum><rsub|k=0><rsup|n>B<rsub|k>*y<rsub|k>
  </equation>

  We now multiply both sides of (53) by <math|p*y<rsub|k>> and integrate
  around the unit circle. Since <math|y<rsub|n><rprime|'>> is orthogonal,
  with weight function <math|x*p>, to any polynomial of degree less than
  <math|n-1>, we find that all the coefficients <math|B<rsub|k>> are zero
  except <math|B<rsub|n>> and <math|B<rsub|n-1>>. Hence:

  <\equation>
    x<rsup|2>*y<rsub|n><rprime|'>=<around|(|A*x+B<rsub|n>|)>*y<rsub|n>+B<rsub|n-1>*y<rsub|n-1>
  </equation>

  We now determine <math|A>, <math|B<rsub|n>>, and <math|B<rsub|n-1>> by
  equating the coefficients of <math|x<rsup|n+1>> and <math|x<rsup|n>>, as
  well as the constant terms, using formula (34). This gives:

  <\equation>
    <tabular|<tformat|<table|<row|<cell|m*<around|(|2*n+a-2|)><around|(|n|)>*x<rsup|n+1>+m*<around|(|n-1|)>*<around|(|2*n+a-3|)>*<around|(|n-1|)>*x<rsup|n>+\<ldots\>>>|<row|<cell|+B<rsub|n>*<around|(|2*n+a-2|)><around|(|n|)>*x<rsup|n>+\<ldots\>+B+\<ldots\>+B<rsub|n-1>>>>>>
  </equation>

  Hence we have:

  <\equation>
    A=<frac|n*<around|(|2*n+a-2|)><around|(|n|)>|<around|(|2*n+a-2|)><around|(|n|)>>=n
  </equation>

  <\equation>
    B<rsub|n>=<frac|<around|(|n*<around|(|n-1|)>*<around|(|2*n+a-3|)>*<around|(|n-1|)>-A<rsub|n>*<around|(|2*n+a-3|)>*<around|(|n-1|)>|)>*b|<around|(|2*n+a-2|)><around|(|n|)>>=<frac|-b*n|2*n+a-2>
  </equation>

  <\equation>
    B<rsub|n-1>=-B<rsub|n>=<frac|b*n|2*n+a-2>
  </equation>

  From (56) and (54) we get the second relation of (51). This completes the
  proof. Other recurrence relations may be derived and proved in the same
  manner.

  <section*|The normalizing factor>

  As in <math|Ÿ*8>, it is desirable to have formulas for

  <\equation>
    <big|int>y<rsub|n><rsup|2>*p<around|(|x|)>*d*x=<big|int><around*|(|-<frac|b|x>|)><rsup|k+1><around|(|k<around|(|n|)>|)>
  </equation>

  <\equation>
    <big|int>x*y<rsub|n>*p<around|(|x|)>*d*x=<frac|<around|(|k+a+n-1|)>*k<rsup|n>|<around|(|-1|)><rsup|n+1><around|(|b!|)><rsup|n>>
  </equation>

  <\equation>
    <big|int>y<rsub|n><rsup|2>*p<around|(|x|)>*d*x=<frac|<around|(|2*n+a-1|)>*<around|(|n+a-2|)><around|(|n|)><rsup|n>|1>
  </equation>

  We prove (57) as follows:

  <\equation*>
    <big|int>x<rsup|k+n>*p<around|(|x|)>*d*x=<frac|1|2*\<pi\>*i>*<big|sum><rsub|p=0><rsup|n><big|sum><rsub|s=0><rsup|\<infty\>><around|(|-1|)><rsup|s+1>*C<rsub|n,p>*<around*|(|n+p+a-2|)>*p<around|(|x|)>*x<rsup|k+p+s-1>
  </equation*>

  <\equation*>
    =<big|sum><rsub|p=0><rsup|n><around|(|-1|)><rsup|k+p+1>*C<rsub|n,p>*<around*|(|n+p+a-2|)><around|(|p<around|(|b|)><rsup|k+1>|)>
  </equation*>

  <\equation*>
    =<frac|<around|(|-b|)><rsup|k+1>*k<around|(|n|)>|<around|(|k+a+n-1|)>*k<rsup|n>>,
  </equation*>

  which gives the formula (57). Note that the right side of (57) is zero for
  <math|k\<less\>n>. We prove (58) from (57), using the orthogonality
  relation (46) together with the explicit formula for
  <math|y<rsub|n><around|(|x|)>>. This gives:

  <\equation*>
    <big|int>y<rsub|n>*p*d*x=<frac|<around|(|2*n+a-2|)>*b<rsup|n>|<around|(|2*n+a-2|)>>*<frac|n<rsup|n>|b<rsup|n>>
  </equation*>

  and replacing the integral on the right side by its value from (57) gives
  formula (58). It follows from (58) that the functions:

  <\equation*>
    <around|[|<around|(|2*n+a-1|)>*<around|(|n+a-2|)><around|(|n|)><rsup|n-1>|]>/b*n!\|2*\<pi\><rsup|2*n+1>*y<rsub|n>*<around|(|x,a,b|)>
  </equation*>

  are orthonormal with weight function <math|p<around|(|x|)>>.

  <section*|Conclusion>

  In Part I we have given a fairly complete theory of the Bessel polynomials
  proper. Other topics that suggest themselves in this case are the location
  of the roots of these polynomials, and the actual expansion of particular
  functions in terms of them. It should be noted that formula (10), which
  expresses traveling spherical waves in terms of the Bessel polynomial
  <math|y<rsub|n>*<around|(|1/i*k*R|)>>, indicates that this function, when
  multiplied by <math|e<rsup|-i*k*R>>, bears the same relation to traveling
  spherical waves that the Hankel function, or Bessel function of the third
  kind, given by:

  <\equation*>
    H<rsub|n>*<around|(|k*r|)>=J<rsub|n>*<around|(|k*r|)>+i*N<rsub|n>*<around|(|k*r|)>
  </equation*>

  bears to traveling cylindrical waves. Thus the Bessel polynomials may be
  thought of as spherical Hankel functions.

  Our investigation of the generalized Bessel polynomials in Part II has not
  been quite so complete. In particular, we have not succeeded in finding a
  generating function for these polynomials. The general case is more
  difficult to treat, one reason being that here one does not have the entire
  theory of Bessel functions to rely on to derive results.\ 

  As we have indicated, the special case of the generalized Bessel
  polynomials where <math|a=1> seems to have particular importance, and may
  deserve as detailed a treatment as we have given in Part I for the case
  <math|a=2>. For example, the polynomials corresponding to integral values
  of <math|a>, whose theory is particularly simple, may all be obtained by
  differentiation from the polynomials with <math|a=1> or <math|2>. We have
  as yet found no application for the case <math|a=1>, however.

  The cases we have excluded where <math|a=0,-1,-2,\<ldots\>> may also be
  worth studying. More attention could be given to the theory of the second
  solution of the differential equation (2). The weight function
  <math|p<around|(|x|)>>, given by formula (36), may also be worth further
  investigation. It is definable in terms of the function
  <math|y<around|(|x,a|)>> given by:

  <\equation>
    y<around|(|x,a|)>=x<rsup|a>*<around*|(|<frac|1|a>+<frac|x|a*<around|(|a+1|)>>+<frac|x<rsup|2>|a*<around|(|a+1|)>*<around|(|a+2|)>>+\<ldots\>|)>
  </equation>

  This function satisfies the differential equation:
  <math|y<rprime|'>-y=x<rsup|a-1>>, and is expressible for positive <math|a>
  by the formula:

  <\equation>
    y<around|(|x,a|)>=e<rsup|x>*<big|int><rsub|0><rsup|x>t<rsup|a-1>*e<rsup|-t>*<space|0.17em>d*t
  </equation>

  It is thus related to the incomplete gamma function, and has various
  interesting properties.

  It would also be useful to have weight functions with respect to which the
  Bessel functions are orthogonal with path of integration along the real
  axis or the imaginary axis. Since in the first recurrence relations of (21)
  and (51) the coefficients of <math|y<rsub|n-1>> are positive, it follows
  from known results that no non-negative weight function exists with path of
  integration along the real axis (see O. Perron, <with|font-shape|italic|Die
  Lehre von den Kettenbrüchen>, Leipzig 1929, p. 376). On the other hand, it
  follows from results of Pólya and Boas that many weight functions of
  Stieltjes type do exist for the real axis.

  Still another question concerns the solutions of the differential equations
  (1) and (2) for non-integral values of <math|n>. The solutions of (1) for
  half-integral <math|n> are expressible in terms of the Bessel functions of
  integral order. For non-integral values of <math|n>, the attempt to solve
  equations (1) and (2) in series of powers of <math|x> leads to merely
  asymptotic series which are divergent. In the case of equation (1) with
  half-integral values of <math|n>, this procedure leads to the well-known
  asymptotic series for the Bessel functions. The appearance of these
  asymptotic series is related to the fact that the equations (1) and (2)
  have a nonregular singular point at <math|x=0>. The differential equations
  for the classical orthogonal polynomials of Jacobi, Laguerre, and Hermite
  have no finite irregular singular points at <math|x=0>.

